%N A395309 Numbers k such that tau(k) = tau(k + d), where d is some divisor of k where tau(i) = A000005(i).
%C A395309 The sequence is infinite as it contains 2*p for odd prime p via 2*p + p for p > 3 or 6+2 for p = 3. - _David A. Corneth_, Apr 25 2026
%t A395309 q[k_] := With[{d = DivisorSigma[0, k]}, AnyTrue[Divisors[k], DivisorSigma[0, k + #] == d &]]; Select[Range[135], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Apr 19 2026 *)
%o A395309 (PARI) isok(k) = my(t=numdiv(k)); fordiv(k, d, if (t==numdiv(k+d), return(1))); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Apr 25 2026
